i really probably didn't need to say all this and it does feel very self-congratulatory to me now which might be the scrupulosity speaking and telling me to apologize n delete it but uh i guess all of that was to say i'll probably be talking about ocd here more often from now on?

also i'm not trying to act like i'm some big important educator doing a lot of good or whatever, it's more just that i've been finding it helpful to me to talk about it, and the idea that it could maybe potentially be beneficial to somebody else also makes me want to do it more?

which is to say please don't assume that all ocd cases have to look like mine or else they're not ocd, or if you think you might have ocd please don't think that just because your experience doesn't really match up with mine then that means you must not actually have ocd

my ocd has manifested as a wide variety of different subtypes over the years so i feel like i have a lot of perspective on the different ways it can present, but it's still always going to be incomplete

additionally, on the off-chance somebody were to read something i write and realize "oh that sounds very familiar, i think i might also have this and it's distressing for me and i think it could be helpful for me to seek treatment" then that would make me happy too

so if more people can realize that they shouldn't be doing things like that through coming to understand what it's really like to have ocd, and how these things can feel dismissive and condescending to us, then that is good, i think

but it's still unhepful for people to say "well everyone's a little ocd sometimes" when you try to talk about your experiences, or to reinforce the notion that it's just being a neat freak or a perfectionist for no reason other than just wanting to take pride in some clean work

i don't really want to like, pull out a yard stick and say "you have to be this paralyzed by your thoughts and anxieties to have ocd," especially when ocd can make you constantly doubt that you even have ocd, and i've had periods of my life where it hasn't been very severe either

it's a widely misunderstood condition, and it sucks to see it so often reduced to just a fun personality quirk when it's been so debilitating to me and many others before. i had to drop out of college because at the time i could do little else but mentally torture myself all day

i've been dealing with various forms of ocd for at least 12 years now, i don't have anything remotely resembling an actual platform but i still hope my talking about my experiences with it can be educational to some
